At 100Gb speed, in order for PFC storm detection to occur on DUT, PFC xoff pkts with max (65535) quanta must arrive from fanout peer at intervals no greater than ~335usecs. This period is how long it takes DUT ASIC to count down its internal xoff event timer to expiry at max quanta. If all PFC pkts arrive within this period (with respect to the xoff pkt sent immediately prior) then ASIC will constantly/consistently reset its internal xoff event timer and begin the countdown to expiry anew. However, if *any* PFC pkt(s) arrive later than this period (~335 usecs after the xoff pkt sent immediately prior) then DUT ASIC internal xoff event timer expires and internal PFC xoff-to-xon condition occurs (so that inbound traffic can again be accepted). The next inbound PFC xoff pkt then results in PFC xon-to-xoff condition (which increments the associated counter). As soon as new PFC xon-to-off transition event is registered in counters table then PFC storm detection lua script decides that no storm is occurring. 

Existing Python fanout script used to originate PFC xoff pkts sends 1 pkt at a time via socket.send() API and is woefully susceptible to interpacket jitter. Thus, the following changes have been made to fanout packet storm origination script:

 - Socket changed from (default) blocking to non-blocking for better understanding of when sending completes or doesn't. 

 - Sending 1000 packets per socket send (via sendmmsg API) in contrast to the single packet currently being sent per socket send (via send API). This significantly reduces the number of userspace-to-kernel context switches at packet send time (one context switch per 1000 pkts instead of 1000 context switches per same number of pkts). 

 - Providing a higher priority for the launched Python interpreter and associated test script via -20 nice value. This provides higher priority scheduling than most other extant non-realtime processes on fanout. Python cannot be launched as a realtime process for this purpose. 

 - Bypassing the utilized raw socket’s kernel assigned queueing discipline for egress traffic by using the PACKET_QDISC_BYPASS socket option. This option facilitates the sending of packets directly to driver egress stage instead of through the kernel’s egress queueing paradigm (discipline). 

 - Sending packet storm for 8 second period instead of specifying an absolute number of packets to send. 

Above modifications now result in a 90+% passing rate (with 10 iterations of 8 second storms each test), however there are still instances where test fails due to excessive jitter and DUT failure to recognize storm. At present we have reduced the number of excessive gaps (that is, > ~335usecs between fanout originated PFC packets) from approximately 1 in 2500 sent pkts to approximately 1 in 50000 pkts (so, somewhere around 20x improvement).
